snippet.textDisplay:
On the topic of Ray's parents. Am I the only person who actually enjoyed that twist? (TL;DR)

When they explained Ray's parents were nobodies, where some could, as you said, cite Chekhov's Gun and say "This isn't a good payoff", I instead saw it and wen't "Woah, what a twist! I love it!" Because I didn't see the identity of Ray's parents as the payoff.
The Chekhov's Gun was pointing to; "Ray's Parent's are important", and we then got the twist of "Ray's parent's are nobodies." Which in inheritly understand as; "The payoff, is why are 'nobodies' important?" Just because her parent's were "Some people from X" doesn't mean they aren't important. New characters, new names, new faces, and new interactions with people old and new.
New Nobodies was inherently the more interesting answer, because if her parents were some characters we already knew, then the buck stops there. We already know them.
Nobodies inserts more questions, which means more questions to answer, which Is what I'm going at here.

TL;DR: A plot hole is FAR more interesting than a story cleanly tied with a bow. A perfect story can't be enhanced or elaborated on, while a imperfect one can.

Theory about S4E5, the whole snake thing could’ve been prevented. It was all Ricks fault. Hear me out:
Rick drives a spaceship with wheels and tires right? Gets a flat tire in space. Whenever they get the flat tire, Rick talks about how the movement and signals are a simulation. This info can be used to infer that flat tires do not act that way without the simulation and wouldn’t cause the spaceship to rattle and shake whenever they’re flying. So rick could’ve waited to change the tire once they got in earths atmosphere or just land it w 3 good tires and 1 flat.
I mean I guess I don’t know how to fly a spaceship or Morty could’ve just stayed in the car. But hey it’s just a theory
